				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Alg=
ebraic manipulation of "true" and "false"</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(disambigu=
ation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Boolean algebra (disambiguation)">Bo=
olean algebra (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">

</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Ma=
thematics">mathematics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mat=
hematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</a>, <b>Bo=
olean algebra</b> is a branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
lgebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>. It differs from <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_algebra" title=3D"Elementary algebra">eleme=
ntary algebra</a> in two ways. First, the values of the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(mathematics)" title=3D"Variable (mathematic=
s)">variables</a> are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truth_va=
lue" title=3D"Truth value">truth values</a> <i>true</i> and <i>false</i>, u=
sually denoted by 1 and 0, whereas in elementary algebra the values of the =
variables are numbers. Second, Boolean algebra uses <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_operator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logical =
operator">logical operators</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logical_conjunction" title=3D"Logical conjunction">conjunction</a> (<=
i>and</i>) denoted as <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=A7</span>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disjunction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"D=
isjunction">disjunction</a> (<i>or</i>) denoted as <span class=3D"texhtml">=
=E2=88=A8</span>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negation" ti=
tle=3D"Negation">negation</a> (<i>not</i>) denoted as <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">=C2=AC</span>. Elementary algebra, on the other hand, uses arithmetic op=
erators such as addition, multiplication, subtraction, and division. Boolea=
n algebra is therefore a formal way of describing <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logical_operation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logical o=
peration">logical operations</a> in the same way that elementary algebra de=
scribes numerical operations.
</p><p>Boolean algebra was introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/George_Boole" title=3D"George Boole">George Boole</a> in his first b=
ook <i>The Mathematical Analysis of Logic</i> (1847),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bo=
ole_2011_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Boole_2011-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and set forth more fully=
 in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An_Investigation_of_the=
_Laws_of_Thought" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"An Investigation of the La=
ws of Thought">An Investigation of the Laws of Thought</a></i> (1854).<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Boole_1854_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Boole_1854-2"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Accordi=
ng to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Vermilye_Huntington" =
title=3D"Edward Vermilye Huntington">Huntington</a>, the term <i>Boolean al=
gebra</i> was first suggested by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
enry_M._Sheffer" title=3D"Henry M. Sheffer">Henry M. Sheffer</a> in 1913,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Huntington_1933_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Huntington_1933-3"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> although <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Sanders_Pei=
rce" title=3D"Charles Sanders Peirce">Charles Sanders Peirce</a> gave the t=
itle "A Boolian [<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sic" title=3D"=
Sic">sic</a></i>] Algebra with One Constant" to the first chapter of his "T=
he Simplest Mathematics" in 1880.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Peirce_1931_4-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cit=
e_note-Peirce_1931-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Boolean algebra has been fundamental in th=
e development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_electroni=
cs" title=3D"Digital electronics">digital electronics</a>, and is provided =
for in all modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_lang=
uage" title=3D"Programming language">programming languages</a>. It is also =
used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set t=
heory">set theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statisti=
cs" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Givant-Halmos_2=
009_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boole=
an_algebra#cite_note-Givant-Halmos_2009-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A precursor of Boolean algebra was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfrie=
d Wilhelm Leibniz</a>'s algebra of concepts. The usage of binary in relatio=
n to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Ching" title=3D"I Ch=
ing">I Ching</a></i> was central to Leibniz's <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Characteristica_universalis" title=3D"Characteristica univer=
salis">characteristica universalis</a></i>. It eventually created the found=
ations of algebra of concepts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-6"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Leibniz's algebra of concepts is deductively equivalent to the Boolean =
algebra of sets.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lenzen_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Lenzen-7"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>Boole's algebra predated the modern developments in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abstr=
act algebra</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_l=
ogic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</a>; it is however se=
en as connected to the origins of both fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dunn-Hard=
egree_2001_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Dunn-Hardegree_2001-8"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In an abstrac=
t setting, Boolean algebra was perfected in the late 19th century by <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Stanley_Jevons" title=3D"William=
 Stanley Jevons">Jevons</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst=
_Schr%C3%B6der_(mathematician)" title=3D"Ernst Schr=C3=B6der (mathematician=
)">Schr=C3=B6der</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Vermi=
lye_Huntington" title=3D"Edward Vermilye Huntington">Huntington</a> and oth=
ers, until it reached the modern conception of an (abstract) <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_structure" title=3D"Mathematical st=
ructure">mathematical structure</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dunn-Hardegree_2001=
_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_=
algebra#cite_note-Dunn-Hardegree_2001-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the empiri=
cal observation that one can manipulate expressions in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra_of_sets" title=3D"Algebra of sets">algebra=
 of sets</a>, by translating them into expressions in Boole's algebra, is e=
xplained in modern terms by saying that the algebra of sets is <i>a</i> <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(structure)" title=3D=
"Boolean algebra (structure)">Boolean algebra</a> (note the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indefinite_article" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Indefinite article">indefinite article</a>). In fact, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._H._Stone" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"M. H. S=
tone">M. H. Stone</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone%27s_re=
presentation_theorem_for_Boolean_algebras" title=3D"Stone's representation =
theorem for Boolean algebras">proved in 1936</a> that every Boolean algebra=
 is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphic" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Isomorphic">isomorphic</a> to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Field_of_sets" title=3D"Field of sets">field of sets</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_not=
e-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1930s, while studying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Switching_circuit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Switching circuit">swit=
ching circuits</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon=
" title=3D"Claude Shannon">Claude Shannon</a> observed that one could also =
apply the rules of Boole's algebra in this setting,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Weis=
stein_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bo=
olean_algebra#cite_note-Weisstein-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and he introduced <i>swit=
ching algebra</i> as a way to analyze and design circuits by algebraic mean=
s in terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_gate" title=3D=
"Logic gate">logic gates</a>. Shannon already had at his disposal the abstr=
act mathematical apparatus, thus he cast his switching algebra as the <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-element_Boolean_algebra" title=
=3D"Two-element Boolean algebra">two-element Boolean algebra</a></i>. In mo=
dern circuit engineering settings, there is little need to consider other B=
oolean algebras, thus "switching algebra" and "Boolean algebra" are often u=
sed interchangeably.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Balabanian-Carlson_2001_12-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cit=
e_note-Balabanian-Carlson_2001-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rajaraman=
-Radhakrishnan_2008_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Rajaraman-Radhakrishnan_2008-13"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Camara_2010_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Camara_2010-14"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_optimization" title=
=3D"Logic optimization">Efficient implementation</a> of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_function" title=3D"Boolean function">Boolean =
functions</a> is a fundamental problem in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Logic_design" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logic design">desi=
gn</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinational_logic" tit=
le=3D"Combinational logic">combinational logic</a> circuits. Modern <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_design_automation" title=3D"El=
ectronic design automation">electronic design automation</a> tools for <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Very-large-scale_integration" title=3D=
"Very-large-scale integration">very-large-scale integration</a> (VLSI) circ=
uits often rely on an efficient representation of Boolean functions known a=
s (reduced ordered) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_decisio=
n_diagram" title=3D"Binary decision diagram">binary decision diagrams</a> (=
BDD) for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic_synthesis" title=3D=
"Logic synthesis">logic synthesis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Formal_verification" title=3D"Formal verification">formal verificat=
ion</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Chen_2007_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Chen_2007-15"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>Logic sentences that can be expressed in classical <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Propositional calculus">propositional calculus</a> have an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_semantics_(mathematical_logic)" titl=
e=3D"Algebraic semantics (mathematical logic)">equivalent expression</a> in=
 Boolean algebra. Thus, <i>Boolean logic</i> is sometimes used to denote pr=
opositional calculus performed in this way.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Parkes_2002_=
16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_=
algebra#cite_note-Parkes_2002-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Barwise-Et=
chemendy_1999_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Barwise-Etchemendy_1999-17"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Goertzel_1994_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Goertzel_1994-18"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Boolean algebra is not sufficient to capture logic formulas using <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantifier_(logic)" title=3D"Quantifier =
(logic)">quantifiers</a>, like those from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/First-order_logic" title=3D"First-order logic">first-order logic</a=
>.
</p><p>Although the development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</a> di=
d not follow Boole's program, the connection between his algebra and logic =
was later put on firm ground in the setting of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Algebraic_logic" title=3D"Algebraic logic">algebraic logic</a>=
, which also studies the algebraic systems of many other logics.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Dunn-Hardegree_2001_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Dunn-Hardegree_2001-8"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_problem" title=
=3D"Decision problem">problem of determining whether</a> the variables of a=
 given Boolean (propositional) formula can be assigned in such a way as to =
make the formula evaluate to true is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Boolean_satisfiability_problem" title=3D"Boolean satisfiabili=
ty problem">Boolean satisfiability problem</a> (SAT), and is of importance =
to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoretical_computer_science" t=
itle=3D"Theoretical computer science">theoretical computer science</a>, bei=
ng the first problem shown to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
P-complete" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NP-complete">NP-complete</a>. Th=
e closely related <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_of_computa=
tion" title=3D"Model of computation">model of computation</a> known as a <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_circuit" title=3D"Boolean=
 circuit">Boolean circuit</a></i> relates <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Time_complexity" title=3D"Time complexity">time complexity</a> (of =
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">=
algorithm</a>) to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit_complexi=
ty" title=3D"Circuit complexity">circuit complexity</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Values">Values</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Values"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Whereas expressions denote mainly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Number" title=3D"Number">numbers</a> in elementary algebra, in Boolean a=
lgebra, they denote the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truth_valu=
es" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Truth values">truth values</a> <i>false<=
/i> and <i>true</i>. These values are represented with the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bits</a>, 0 and 1. They do not =
behave like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"=
Integer">integers</a> 0 and 1, for which <span class=3D"texhtml">1 + 1 =3D =
2</span>, but may be identified with the elements of the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GF(2)" title=3D"GF(2)">two-element field <span class=
=3D"texhtml">GF(2)</span></a>, that is, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">integer arithmetic m=
odulo 2</a>, for which <span class=3D"texhtml">1 + 1 =3D 0</span>. Addition=
 and multiplication then play the Boolean roles of XOR (exclusive-or) and A=
ND (conjunction), respectively, with disjunction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i></span> (inclusive-or) definable as <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>x</i> + <i>y</i> =E2=88=92 <i>xy</i></span> and negation <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">=C2=AC<i>x</i></span> as <span class=3D"texhtml">1 =E2=
=88=92 <i>x</i></span>. In <span class=3D"texhtml">GF(2)</span>, <span clas=
s=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var(--border-color-muted,#ddd=
); color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-color: var( --background-co=
lor-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">=E2=88=92</span> may be re=
placed by <span class=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var(--bor=
der-color-muted,#ddd); color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-color: =
var( --background-color-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">+</spa=
n>, since they denote the same operation; however, this way of writing Bool=
ean operations allows applying the usual arithmetic operations of integers =
(this may be useful when using a programming language in which <span class=
=3D"texhtml">GF(2)</span> is not implemented).
</p><p>Boolean algebra also deals with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functions</a>=
 which have their values in the set <span class=3D"texhtml">{0,1}</span>. A=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bit_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Bit vector">sequence of bits</a> is a commonly used example of su=
ch a function. Another common example is the totality of subsets of a set <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i></span>: to a subset <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>F</i></span> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i></span>, one can define=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicator_function" title=3D"=
Indicator function">indicator function</a> that takes the value <span class=
=3D"texhtml">1</span> on <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i></span>, and <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">0</span> outside <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i></span>=
. The most general example is the set elements of a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(structure)" title=3D"Boolean algebra (st=
ructure)">Boolean algebra</a>, with all of the foregoing being instances th=
ereof.
</p><p>As with elementary algebra, the purely equational part of the theory=
 may be developed, without considering explicit values for the variables.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Halmos_1963_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Halmos_1963-19"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
