<dl><dt><b>Material conditional</b></dt>
<dd>The first operation, <i>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=86=92&nbsp;<i>y</i>, or C<i>xy</=
i>, is called <i>material implication</i>. If <i>x</i> is true, then the re=
sult of expression <i>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=86=92&nbsp;<i>y</i> is taken to be tha=
t of <i>y</i> (e.g. if <i>x</i> is true and <i>y</i> is false, then <i>x</i=
>&nbsp;=E2=86=92&nbsp;<i>y</i> is also false). But if <i>x</i> is false, th=
en the value of <i>y</i> can be ignored; however, the operation must return=
 <i>some</i> Boolean value and there are only two choices. So by definition=
, <i>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=86=92&nbsp;<i>y</i> is <i>true</i> when x is false (<a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relevance_logic" title=3D"Relevance l=
ogic">relevance logic</a> rejects this definition, by viewing an implicatio=
n with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False_premise" title=3D"F=
alse premise">false premise</a> as something other than either true or fals=
e).</dd>
<dt><b>Exclusive OR</b> (<b>XOR</b>)</dt>
<dd>The second operation, <i>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=8A=95&nbsp;<i>y</i>, or J<i>xy<=
/i>, is called <i>exclusive or</i> (often abbreviated as XOR) to distinguis=
h it from disjunction as the inclusive kind. It excludes the possibility of=
 both <i>x</i> and <i>y being</i> true (e.g. see table): if both are true t=
hen result is false. Defined in terms of arithmetic it is addition where mo=
d 2 is 1&nbsp;+&nbsp;1 =3D&nbsp;0.</dd>
<dt><b>Logical equivalence</b></dt>
<dd>The third operation, the complement of exclusive or, is <i>equivalence<=
/i> or Boolean equality: <i>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A1&nbsp;<i>y</i>, or E<i>xy</=
i>, is true just when <i>x</i> and <i>y</i> have the same value. Hence <i>x=
</i>&nbsp;=E2=8A=95&nbsp;<i>y</i> as its complement can be understood as <i=
>x</i>&nbsp;=E2=89=A0&nbsp;<i>y</i>, being true just when <i>x</i> and <i>y=
</i> are different. Thus, its counterpart in arithmetic mod 2 is <i>x</i> +=
 <i>y</i>. Equivalence's counterpart in arithmetic mod 2 is <i>x</i> + <i>y=
</i> + 1.</dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Laws">Laws</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Laws"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <i>law</i> of Boolean algebra is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Identity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Identity (mathematics)">identity</a=
> such as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 (<i>y</i> =E2=88=A8 <i=
>z</i>) =3D (<i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i>) =E2=88=A8 <i>z</i></span> between=
 two Boolean terms, where a <i>Boolean term</i> is defined as an expression=
 built up from variables and the constants 0 and 1 using the operations =E2=
=88=A7, =E2=88=A8, and =C2=AC. The concept can be extended to terms involvi=
ng other Boolean operations such as =E2=8A=95, =E2=86=92, and =E2=89=A1, bu=
t such extensions are unnecessary for the purposes to which the laws are pu=
t. Such purposes include the definition of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#Boolean_algebras">Boolean algebra</a> as any <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_(logic)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Model (logic)">model</a> of the Boolean laws, and as a means for d=
eriving new laws from old as in the derivation of <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 (<i>y</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>z</i>) =3D <i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 (<i>=
z</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i>)</span> from <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =E2=
=88=A7 <i>z</i> =3D <i>z</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i></span> (as treated in <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#Axiomatizing_Boolean=
_algebra">=C2=A7&nbsp;Axiomatizing Boolean algebra</a></i>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Monotone_laws">Monotone law=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_al=
gebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Monotone la=
ws"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Boolean algebra satisfies many of the same laws as ordinary algebra when=
 one matches up =E2=88=A8 with addition and =E2=88=A7 with multiplication. =
In particular the following laws are common to both kinds of algebra:<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-ORegan_2008_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-ORegan_2008-25"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-EoBA_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-EoBA-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><table>

<tbody><tr>
<td>Associativity of <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=A8</span>:</td>
