<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Completeness">Completeness<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_alge=
bra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Completeness"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>The laws listed above define Boolean algebra, in the sense that they ent=
ail the rest of the subject. The laws <i>complementation</i> 1 and 2, toget=
her with the monotone laws, suffice for this purpose and can therefore be t=
aken as one possible <i>complete</i> set of laws or <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatiza=
tion">axiomatization</a> of Boolean algebra. Every law of Boolean algebra f=
ollows logically from these axioms. Furthermore, Boolean algebras can then =
be defined as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_(logic)" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Model (logic)">models</a> of these axioms as =
treated in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#Bool=
ean_algebras">=C2=A7&nbsp;Boolean algebras</a></i>.
</p><p>Writing down further laws of Boolean algebra cannot give rise to any=
 new consequences of these axioms, nor can it rule out any model of them. I=
n contrast, in a list of some but not all of the same laws, there could hav=
e been Boolean laws that did not follow from those on the list, and moreove=
r there would have been models of the listed laws that were not Boolean alg=
ebras.
</p><p>This axiomatization is by no means the only one, or even necessarily=
 the most natural given that attention was not paid as to whether some of t=
he axioms followed from others, but there was simply a choice to stop when =
enough laws had been noticed, treated further in <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#Axiomatizing_Boolean_algebra">=C2=A7&nbsp=
;Axiomatizing Boolean algebra</a></i>. Or the intermediate notion of axiom =
can be sidestepped altogether by defining a Boolean law directly as any <i>=
tautology</i>, understood as an equation that holds for all values of its v=
ariables over 0 and 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-McGee_2005_27-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-McGe=
e_2005-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Goodstein_2012_28-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-=
Goodstein_2012-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> All these definitions of Boolean algebra can=
 be shown to be equivalent.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Duality_principle">Duality =
principle</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBo=
olean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Du=
ality principle"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjunction/disjunct=
ion_duality" title=3D"Conjunction/disjunction duality">Conjunction/disjunct=
ion duality</a></div>
<p>Principle: If {X, R} is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parti=
ally_ordered_set" title=3D"Partially ordered set">partially ordered set</a>=
, then {X, R(inverse)} is also a partially ordered set.
</p><p>There is nothing special about the choice of symbols for the values =
of Boolean algebra. 0 and 1 could be renamed to <i>=CE=B1</i> and <i>=CE=B2=
</i>, and as long as it was done consistently throughout, it would still be=
 Boolean algebra, albeit with some obvious cosmetic differences.
</p><p>But suppose 0 and 1 were renamed 1 and 0 respectively. Then it would=
 still be Boolean algebra, and moreover operating on the same values. Howev=
er, it would not be identical to our original Boolean algebra because now =
=E2=88=A8 behaves the way =E2=88=A7 used to do and vice versa. So there are=
 still some cosmetic differences to show that the notation has been changed=
, despite the fact that 0s and 1s are still being used.
</p><p>But if in addition to interchanging the names of the values, the nam=
es of the two binary operations are also interchanged, <i>now</i> there is =
no trace of what was done. The end product is completely indistinguishable =
from what was started with. The columns for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i=
> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 =
<i>y</i></span> in the truth tables have changed places, but that switch is=
 immaterial.
</p><p>When values and operations can be paired up in a way that leaves eve=
rything important unchanged when all pairs are switched simultaneously, the=
 members of each pair are called <i>dual</i> to each other. Thus 0 and 1 ar=
e dual, and =E2=88=A7 and =E2=88=A8 are dual. The <i>duality principle</i>,=
 also called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Morgan_duality" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"De Morgan duality">De Morgan duality</a>, asse=
rts that Boolean algebra is unchanged when all dual pairs are interchanged.
</p><p>One change not needed to make as part of this interchange was to com=
plement. Complement is a <i>self-dual</i> operation. The identity or do-not=
hing operation <i>x</i> (copy the input to the output) is also self-dual. A=
 more complicated example of a self-dual operation is <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">(<i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i>) =E2=88=A8 (<i>y</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>z</i>) =
=E2=88=A8 (<i>z</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>x</i>)</span>. There is no self-dual binar=
y operation that depends on both its arguments. A composition of self-dual =
operations is a self-dual operation. For example, if <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>f</i>(<i>x</i>, <i>y</i>, <i>z</i>) =3D (<i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i>) =
=E2=88=A8 (<i>y</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>z</i>) =E2=88=A8 (<i>z</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>x<=
/i>)</span>, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>, <i>y<=
/i>, <i>z</i>), <i>x</i>, <i>t</i>)</span> is a self-dual operation of four=
 arguments <i>x</i>, <i>y</i>, <i>z</i>, <i>t</i>.
</p><p>The principle of duality can be explained from a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>=
 perspective by the fact that there are exactly four functions that are one=
-to-one mappings (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automorphism" ti=
tle=3D"Automorphism">automorphisms</a>) of the set of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bool=
ean polynomial">Boolean polynomials</a> back to itself: the identity functi=
on, the complement function, the dual function and the contradual function =
(complemented dual). These four functions form a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Group_(mathematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">group</a>=
 under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_composition" title=
=3D"Function composition">function composition</a>, isomorphic to the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klein_four-group" title=3D"Klein four-g=
roup">Klein four-group</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_=
action_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Group action (mathemat=
ics)">acting</a> on the set of Boolean polynomials. <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Gottschalk" title=3D"Walter Gottschalk">Walter Got=
tschalk</a> remarked that consequently a more appropriate name for the phen=
omenon would be the <i>principle</i> (or <i>square</i>) <i>of quaternality<=
/i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Givant-Halmos_2009_5-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Givant-Halmos_2=
009-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 21=
=E2=80=9322">:=E2=80=8A21=E2=80=9322=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Diagrammatic_representation=
s">Diagrammatic representations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Diagrammatic representations"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Venn_diagrams">Venn diagram=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_al=
gebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Venn diagr=
ams"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagram" title=3D"Venn d=
iagram">Venn diagram</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Venn_1880_29-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Ven=
n_1880-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> can be used as a representation of a Boolean operati=
on using shaded overlapping regions. There is one region for each variable,=
 all circular in the examples here. The interior and exterior of region <i>=
x</i> corresponds respectively to the values 1 (true) and 0 (false) for var=
iable <i>x</i>. The shading indicates the value of the operation for each c=
ombination of regions, with dark denoting 1 and light 0 (some authors use t=
he opposite convention).
</p><p>The three Venn diagrams in the figure below represent respectively c=
onjunction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i></span>, disj=
unction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i></span>, and com=
plement =C2=AC<i>x</i>.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Vennandornot.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descripti=
on"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/V=
ennandornot.svg/500px-Vennandornot.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"500=
" height=3D"172" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"851" data-fil=
e-height=3D"293"></a><figcaption>Figure 2. Venn diagrams for conjunction, d=
isjunction, and complement</figcaption></figure>
<p>For conjunction, the region inside both circles is shaded to indicate th=
at <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i></span> is 1 when bot=
h variables are 1. The other regions are left unshaded to indicate that <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i></span> is 0 for the other =
three combinations.
</p><p>The second diagram represents disjunction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i></span> by shading those regions that lie inside e=
ither or both circles. The third diagram represents complement =C2=AC<i>x</=
i> by shading the region <i>not</i> inside the circle.
</p><p>While we have not shown the Venn diagrams for the constants 0 and 1,=
 they are trivial, being respectively a white box and a dark box, neither o=
ne containing a circle. However, we could put a circle for <i>x</i> in thos=
e boxes, in which case each would denote a function of one argument, <i>x</=
i>, which returns the same value independently of <i>x</i>, called a consta=
nt function. As far as their outputs are concerned, constants and constant =
functions are indistinguishable; the difference is that a constant takes no=
 arguments, called a <i>zeroary</i> or <i>nullary</i> operation, while a co=
nstant function takes one argument, which it ignores, and is a <i>unary</i>=
 operation.
</p><p>Venn diagrams are helpful in visualizing laws. The commutativity law=
s for =E2=88=A7 and =E2=88=A8 can be seen from the symmetry of the diagrams=
: a binary operation that was not commutative would not have a symmetric di=
agram because interchanging <i>x</i> and <i>y</i> would have the effect of =
reflecting the diagram horizontally and any failure of commutativity would =
then appear as a failure of symmetry.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idempotence" title=3D"Idemp=
otence">Idempotence</a> of =E2=88=A7 and =E2=88=A8 can be visualized by sli=
ding the two circles together and noting that the shaded area then becomes =
the whole circle, for both =E2=88=A7 and =E2=88=A8.
</p><p>To see the first absorption law, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =
=E2=88=A7 (<i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i>) =3D <i>x</i></span>, start with the=
 diagram in the middle for <i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i> and note that the po=
rtion of the shaded area in common with the <i>x</i> circle is the whole of=
 the <i>x</i> circle. For the second absorption law, <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 (<i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i>) =3D <i>x</i></span>, sta=
rt with the left diagram for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i>=E2=88=A7<i>y<=
/i></span> and note that shading the whole of the <i>x</i> circle results i=
n just the <i>x</i> circle being shaded, since the previous shading was ins=
ide the <i>x</i> circle.
</p><p>The double negation law can be seen by complementing the shading in =
the third diagram for =C2=AC<i>x</i>, which shades the <i>x</i> circle.
</p><p>To visualize the first De Morgan's law, <span class=3D"texhtml">(=C2=
=AC<i>x</i>) =E2=88=A7 (=C2=AC<i>y</i>) =3D =C2=AC(<i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y<=
/i>)</span>, start with the middle diagram for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x=
</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i></span> and complement its shading so that only the =
region outside both circles is shaded, which is what the right hand side of=
 the law describes. The result is the same as if we shaded that region whic=
h is both outside the <i>x</i> circle <i>and</i> outside the <i>y</i> circl=
e, i.e. the conjunction of their exteriors, which is what the left hand sid=
e of the law describes.
</p><p>The second De Morgan's law, <span class=3D"texhtml">(=C2=AC<i>x</i>)=
 =E2=88=A8 (=C2=AC<i>y</i>) =3D =C2=AC(<i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>y</i>)</span>,=
 works the same way with the two diagrams interchanged.
</p><p>The first complement law, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A7=
 =C2=AC<i>x</i> =3D 0</span>, says that the interior and exterior of the <i=
>x</i> circle have no overlap. The second complement law, <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 =C2=AC<i>x</i> =3D 1</span>, says that everything=
 is either inside or outside the <i>x</i> circle.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Digital_logic_gates">Digita=
l logic gates</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Digital logic gates"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Digital logic is the application of the Boolean algebra of 0 and 1 to el=
ectronic hardware consisting of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
gic_gates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logic gates">logic gates</a> conn=
ected to form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit_diagram" t=
itle=3D"Circuit diagram">circuit diagram</a>. Each gate implements a Boolea=
n operation, and is depicted schematically by a shape indicating the operat=
ion. The shapes associated with the gates for conjunction (AND-gates), disj=
unction (OR-gates), and complement (inverters) are as follows:<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Shannon_1949_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Shannon_1949-30"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-center skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thum=
b"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:LogicGates.svg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/c/c1/LogicGates.svg/500px-LogicGates.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" =
width=3D"400" height=3D"48" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"90=
8" data-file-height=3D"110"></a><figcaption>From left to right: <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AND_gate" title=3D"AND gate">AND</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OR_gate" title=3D"OR gate">OR</a>, and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverter_(logic_gate)" title=3D"Inve=
rter (logic gate)">NOT</a> gates.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The lines on the left of each gate represent input wires or <i>ports</i>=
. The value of the input is represented by a voltage on the lead. For so-ca=
lled "active-high" logic, 0 is represented by a voltage close to zero or "g=
round," while 1 is represented by a voltage close to the supply voltage; ac=
tive-low reverses this. The line on the right of each gate represents the o=
utput port, which normally follows the same voltage conventions as the inpu=
t ports.
</p><p>Complement is implemented with an inverter gate. The triangle denote=
s the operation that simply copies the input to the output; the small circl=
e on the output denotes the actual inversion complementing the input. The c=
onvention of putting such a circle on any port means that the signal passin=
g through this port is complemented on the way through, whether it is an in=
put or output port.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#Duality=
_principle">duality principle</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/De_Morgan%27s_laws" title=3D"De Morgan's laws">De Morgan's laws</a>, ca=
n be understood as asserting that complementing all three ports of an AND g=
ate converts it to an OR gate and vice versa, as shown in Figure 4 below. C=
omplementing both ports of an inverter however leaves the operation unchang=
ed.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-center skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thum=
b"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:DeMorganGates.GIF" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/3/3a/DeMorganGates.GIF/500px-DeMorganGates.GIF" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"400" height=3D"82" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-widt=
h=3D"921" data-file-height=3D"189"></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
<p>More generally, one may complement any of the eight subsets of the three=
 ports of either an AND or OR gate. The resulting sixteen possibilities giv=
e rise to only eight Boolean operations, namely those with an odd number of=
 1s in their truth table. There are eight such because the "odd-bit-out" ca=
n be either 0 or 1 and can go in any of four positions in the truth table. =
There being sixteen binary Boolean operations, this must leave eight operat=
ions with an even number of 1s in their truth tables. Two of these are the =
constants 0 and 1 (as binary operations that ignore both their inputs); fou=
r are the operations that depend nontrivially on exactly one of their two i=
nputs, namely <i>x</i>, <i>y</i>, =C2=AC<i>x</i>, and =C2=AC<i>y</i>; and t=
he remaining two are <i>x</i> =E2=8A=95 <i>y</i> (XOR) and its complement <=
i>x</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>y</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Boolean_algebras">Boolean a=
lgebras</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Bool=
ean algebras"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(str=
ucture)" title=3D"Boolean algebra (structure)">Boolean algebra (structure)<=
/a></div>
<p>The term "algebra" denotes both a subject, namely the subject of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>, a=
nd an object, namely an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_=
structure" title=3D"Algebraic structure">algebraic structure</a>. Whereas t=
he foregoing has addressed the subject of Boolean algebra, this section dea=
ls with mathematical objects called Boolean algebras, defined in full gener=
ality as any model of the Boolean laws. We begin with a special case of the=
 notion definable without reference to the laws, namely concrete Boolean al=
gebras, and then give <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_alge=
bra#Boolean_algebras:_the_definition">the formal definition</a> of the gene=
ral notion.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Concrete_Boolean_algebras">=
Concrete Boolean algebras</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"=
Edit section: Concrete Boolean algebras"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <i>concrete Boolean algebra</i> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Field_of_sets" title=3D"Field of sets">field of sets</a> is any nonem=
pty set of subsets of a given set <i>X</i> closed under the set operations =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_(set_theory)" title=3D"Un=
ion (set theory)">union</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter=
section_(set_theory)" title=3D"Intersection (set theory)">intersection</a>,=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complement_(set_theory)#Relat=
ive_complement" title=3D"Complement (set theory)">complement</a> relative t=
o <i>X</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Givant-Halmos_2009_5-4" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Givant-H=
almos_2009-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>(Historically <i>X</i> itself was required to be nonempty as well to=
 exclude the degenerate or one-element Boolean algebra, which is the one ex=
ception to the rule that all Boolean algebras satisfy the same equations si=
nce the degenerate algebra satisfies every equation. However, this exclusio=
n conflicts with the preferred purely equational definition of "Boolean alg=
ebra", there being no way to rule out the one-element algebra using only eq=
uations=E2=80=94&nbsp;0&nbsp;=E2=89=A0&nbsp;1 does not count, being a negat=
ed equation. Hence modern authors allow the degenerate Boolean algebra and =
let <i>X</i> be empty.)
</p><p><i>Example 1.</i> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power=
_set" title=3D"Power set">power set</a> 2<sup><i>X</i></sup> of <i>X</i>, c=
onsisting of all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"=
Subset">subsets</a> of <i>X</i>. Here <i>X</i> may be any set: empty, finit=
e, infinite, or even <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncountable" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uncountable">uncountable</a>.
</p><p><i>Example 2.</i> The empty set and <i>X</i>. This two-element algeb=
ra shows that a concrete Boolean algebra can be finite even when it consist=
s of subsets of an infinite set. It can be seen that every field of subsets=
 of <i>X</i> must contain the empty set and <i>X</i>. Hence no smaller exam=
ple is possible, other than the degenerate algebra obtained by taking <i>X<=
/i> to be empty so as to make the empty set and <i>X</i> coincide.
</p><p><i>Example 3.</i> The set of finite and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cofinite" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cofinite">cofinite</a=
> sets of integers, where a cofinite set is one omitting only finitely many=
 integers. This is clearly closed under complement, and is closed under uni=
on because the union of a cofinite set with any set is cofinite, while the =
union of two finite sets is finite. Intersection behaves like union with "f=
inite" and "cofinite" interchanged. This example is countably infinite beca=
use there are only countably many finite sets of integers.
</p><p><i>Example 4.</i> For a less trivial example of the point made by ex=
ample 2, consider a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagram" =
title=3D"Venn diagram">Venn diagram</a> formed by <i>n</i> closed curves <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_a_set" title=3D"Partiti=
on of a set">partitioning</a> the diagram into 2<sup><i>n</i></sup> regions=
, and let <i>X</i> be the (infinite) set of all points in the plane not on =
any curve but somewhere within the diagram. The interior of each region is =
thus an infinite subset of <i>X</i>, and every point in <i>X</i> is in exac=
tly one region. Then the set of all 2<sup><span>2<sup><i>n</i></sup></span>=
</sup> possible unions of regions (including the empty set obtained as the =
union of the empty set of regions and <i>X</i> obtained as the union of all=
 2<sup><i>n</i></sup> regions) is closed under union, intersection, and com=
plement relative to <i>X</i> and therefore forms a concrete Boolean algebra=
. Again, there are finitely many subsets of an infinite set forming a concr=
ete Boolean algebra, with example 2 arising as the case <i>n</i> =3D 0 of n=
o curves.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Subsets_as_bit_vectors">Sub=
sets as bit vectors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Subsets as bit vectors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A subset <i>Y</i> of <i>X</i> can be identified with an <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indexed_family" title=3D"Indexed family">indexed f=
amily</a> of bits with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Index_set" =
title=3D"Index set">index set</a> <i>X</i>, with the bit indexed by <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=88 <i>X</i></span> being 1 or 0 according =
to whether or not <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=88 <i>Y</i></span=
>. (This is the so-called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicato=
r_function" title=3D"Indicator function">characteristic function</a> notion=
 of a subset.) For example, a 32-bit computer word consists of 32 bits inde=
xed by the set {0,1,2,...,31}, with 0 and 31 indexing the low and high orde=
r bits respectively. For a smaller example, if <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 X=3D\{a,b,c\}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">{</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">}</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X=3D\{a,b,c\}=
}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/36964a6c0376aed739ef2645a5ff6a8d659744d9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:12.705ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X=
=3D\{a,b,c\}}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span> where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">a, b, c</span> are viewed as bit positions in t=
hat order from left to right, the eight subsets {}, {<i>c</i>}, {<i>b</i>},=
 {<i>b</i>,<i>c</i>}, {<i>a</i>}, {<i>a</i>,<i>c</i>}, {<i>a</i>,<i>b</i>},=
 and {<i>a</i>,<i>b</i>,<i>c</i>} of <i>X</i> can be identified with the re=
spective bit vectors 000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, and 111. Bit vector=
s indexed by the set of natural numbers are infinite <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequences</a> of bits, whil=
e those indexed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number=
" title=3D"Real number">reals</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Unit_interval" title=3D"Unit interval">unit interval</a> [0,1] are p=
acked too densely to be able to write conventionally but nonetheless form w=
ell-defined indexed families (imagine coloring every point of the interval =
[0,1] either black or white independently; the black points then form an ar=
bitrary subset of [0,1]).
</p><p>From this bit vector viewpoint, a concrete Boolean algebra can be de=
fined equivalently as a nonempty set of bit vectors all of the same length =
(more generally, indexed by the same set) and closed under the bit vector o=
perations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Bitwise">bitwise</a> =E2=88=A7, =E2=88=A8, and =C2=AC, a=
s in <span class=3D"texhtml">1010=E2=88=A70110 =3D 0010</span>, <span class=
=3D"texhtml">1010=E2=88=A80110 =3D 1110</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>=C2=AC1010 =3D 0101</span>, the bit vector realizations of intersection, u=
nion, and complement respectively.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prototypical_Boolean_algebr=
a">Prototypical Boolean algebra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Prototypical Boolean algebra"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-element_Boolean_=
algebra" title=3D"Two-element Boolean algebra">Two-element Boolean algebra<=
/a></div>
<p>The set {0,1} and its Boolean operations as treated above can be underst=
ood as the special case of bit vectors of length one, which by the identifi=
cation of bit vectors with subsets can also be understood as the two subset=
s of a one-element set. This is called the <i>prototypical</i> Boolean alge=
bra, justified by the following observation.
</p>
<dl><dd>The laws satisfied by all nondegenerate concrete Boolean algebras c=
oincide with those satisfied by the prototypical Boolean algebra.</dd></dl>
<p>This observation is proved as follows. Certainly any law satisfied by al=
l concrete Boolean algebras is satisfied by the prototypical one since it i=
s concrete. Conversely any law that fails for some concrete Boolean algebra=
 must have failed at a particular bit position, in which case that position=
 by itself furnishes a one-bit counterexample to that law. Nondegeneracy en=
sures the existence of at least one bit position because there is only one =
empty bit vector.
</p><p>The final goal of the next section can be understood as eliminating =
"concrete" from the above observation. That goal is reached via the stronge=
r observation that, up to isomorphism, all Boolean algebras are concrete.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Boolean_algebras:_the_defin=
ition">Boolean algebras: the definition</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Boolean algebras: the definition"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Boolean algebras so far have all been concrete, consisting of bit ve=
ctors or equivalently of subsets of some set. Such a Boolean algebra consis=
ts of a set and operations on that set which can be <i>shown</i> to satisfy=
 the laws of Boolean algebra.
</p><p>Instead of showing that the Boolean laws are satisfied, we can inste=
ad postulate a set <i>X</i>, two binary operations on <i>X</i>, and one una=
ry operation, and <i>require</i> that those operations satisfy the laws of =
Boolean algebra. The elements of <i>X</i> need not be bit vectors or subset=
s but can be anything at all. This leads to the more general <i>abstract</i=
> definition.
</p>
<dl><dd>A <i>Boolean algebra</i> is any set with binary operations =E2=88=
=A7 and =E2=88=A8 and a unary operation =C2=AC thereon satisfying the Boole=
an laws.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Koppelberg_1989_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Koppelberg_19=
89-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>For the purposes of this definition it is irrelevant how the operations =
came to satisfy the laws, whether by fiat or proof. All concrete Boolean al=
gebras satisfy the laws (by proof rather than fiat), whence every concrete =
Boolean algebra is a Boolean algebra according to our definitions. This axi=
omatic definition of a Boolean algebra as a set and certain operations sati=
sfying certain laws or axioms <i>by fiat</i> is entirely analogous to the a=
bstract definitions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_(math=
ematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">group</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">ring</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"Fie=
ld (mathematics)">field</a> etc. characteristic of modern or <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abs=
tract algebra</a>.
</p><p>Given any complete axiomatization of Boolean algebra, such as the ax=
ioms for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complemented_lattice" t=
itle=3D"Complemented lattice">complemented</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Distributive_lattice" title=3D"Distributive lattice">distribut=
ive lattice</a>, a sufficient condition for an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Algebraic_structure" title=3D"Algebraic structure">algebraic s=
tructure</a> of this kind to satisfy all the Boolean laws is that it satisf=
y just those axioms. The following is therefore an equivalent definition.
</p>
<dl><dd>A <i>Boolean algebra</i> is a complemented distributive lattice.</d=
d></dl>
<p>The section on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#=
Axiomatizing_Boolean_algebra">axiomatization</a> lists other axiomatization=
s, any of which can be made the basis of an equivalent definition.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Representable_Boolean_algeb=
ras">Representable Boolean algebras</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Representable Boolean algebras"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Although every concrete Boolean algebra is a Boolean algebra, not every =
Boolean algebra need be concrete. Let <i>n</i> be a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Square-free_integer" title=3D"Square-free integer">square=
-free</a> positive integer, one not divisible by the square of an integer, =
for example 30 but not 12. The operations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divisor" title=3D"Greatest common divisor">great=
est common divisor</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_comm=
on_multiple" title=3D"Least common multiple">least common multiple</a>, and=
 division into <i>n</i> (that is, =C2=AC<i>x</i> =3D <i>n</i>/<i>x</i>), ca=
n be shown to satisfy all the Boolean laws when their arguments range over =
the positive divisors of <i>n</i>. Hence those divisors form a Boolean alge=
bra. These divisors are not subsets of a set, making the divisors of <i>n</=
i> a Boolean algebra that is not concrete according to our definitions.
</p><p>However, if each divisor of <i>n</i> is <i>represented</i> by the se=
t of its prime factors, this nonconcrete Boolean algebra is <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isomor=
phic">isomorphic</a> to the concrete Boolean algebra consisting of all sets=
 of prime factors of <i>n</i>, with union corresponding to least common mul=
tiple, intersection to greatest common divisor, and complement to division =
into <i>n</i>. So this example, while not technically concrete, is at least=
 "morally" concrete via this representation, called an <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphism" title=3D"Isomorphism">isomorphism</a>. Th=
is example is an instance of the following notion.
</p>
<dl><dd>A Boolean algebra is called <i>representable</i> when it is isomorp=
hic to a concrete Boolean algebra.</dd></dl>
<p>The next question is answered positively as follows.
</p>
<dl><dd>Every Boolean algebra is representable.</dd></dl>
<p>That is, up to isomorphism, abstract and concrete Boolean algebras are t=
he same thing. This result depends on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Boolean_prime_ideal_theorem" title=3D"Boolean prime ideal theorem">=
Boolean prime ideal theorem</a>, a choice principle slightly weaker than th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom =
of choice">axiom of choice</a>. This strong relationship implies a weaker r=
esult strengthening the observation in the previous subsection to the follo=
wing easy consequence of representability.
</p>
<dl><dd>The laws satisfied by all Boolean algebras coincide with those sati=
sfied by the prototypical Boolean algebra.</dd></dl>
<p>It is weaker in the sense that it does not of itself imply representabil=
ity. Boolean algebras are special here, for example a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relation_algebra" title=3D"Relation algebra">relation a=
lgebra</a> is a Boolean algebra with additional structure but it is not the=
 case that every relation algebra is representable in the sense appropriate=
 to relation algebras.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Axiomatizing_Boolean_algebr=
a">Axiomatizing Boolean algebra</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Axiomatizing Boolean algebra"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatization_of_B=
oolean_algebras" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatization of Boolean a=
lgebras">Axiomatization of Boolean algebras</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebras_canonically_defined" title=3D"Boolean al=
gebras canonically defined">Boolean algebras canonically defined</a></div>
<p>The above definition of an abstract Boolean algebra as a set together wi=
th operations satisfying "the" Boolean laws raises the question of what tho=
se laws are. A simplistic answer is "all Boolean laws", which can be define=
d as all equations that hold for the Boolean algebra of 0 and 1. However, s=
ince there are infinitely many such laws, this is not a satisfactory answer=
 in practice, leading to the question of it suffices to require only finite=
ly many laws to hold.
</p><p>In the case of Boolean algebras, the answer is "yes": the finitely m=
any equations listed above are sufficient. Thus, Boolean algebra is said to=
 be <i>finitely axiomatizable</i> or <i>finitely based</i>.
</p><p>Moreover, the number of equations needed can be further reduced. To =
begin with, some of the above laws are implied by some of the others. A suf=
ficient subset of the above laws consists of the pairs of associativity, co=
mmutativity, and absorption laws, distributivity of =E2=88=A7 over =E2=88=
=A8 (or the other distributivity law=E2=80=94one suffices), and the two com=
plement laws. In fact, this is the traditional axiomatization of Boolean al=
gebra as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complemented_lattice" t=
itle=3D"Complemented lattice">complemented</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Distributive_lattice" title=3D"Distributive lattice">distribut=
ive lattice</a>.
</p><p>By introducing additional laws not listed above, it becomes possible=
 to shorten the list of needed equations yet further; for instance, with th=
e vertical bar representing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sh=
effer_stroke" title=3D"Sheffer stroke">Sheffer stroke</a> operation, the si=
ngle axiom <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span c=
