<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Propositional_logic">Propos=
itional logic</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Propositional logic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_calcul=
us" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Propositional calculus">Propositional ca=
lculus</a></div>
<p><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_logic" title=
=3D"Propositional logic">Propositional logic</a></i> is a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logi=
cal system">logical system</a> that is intimately connected to Boolean alge=
bra.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Givant-Halmos_2009_5-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Givant-Halmos_2=
009-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Many syntactic concepts of Boolean algebra carry over to =
propositional logic with only minor changes in notation and terminology, wh=
ile the semantics of propositional logic are defined via Boolean algebras i=
n a way that the tautologies (theorems) of propositional logic correspond t=
o equational theorems of Boolean algebra.
</p><p>Syntactically, every Boolean term corresponds to a <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_formula" title=3D"Propositional fo=
rmula">propositional formula</a></i> of propositional logic. In this transl=
ation between Boolean algebra and propositional logic, Boolean variables <i=
>x, y,</i> ... become <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositi=
onal_variable" title=3D"Propositional variable">propositional variables</a>=
</i> (or <i>atoms</i>) <i>P, Q</i>, ... Boolean terms such as <i>x</i> =E2=
=88=A8 <i>y</i> become propositional formulas <i>P</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>Q</i>; =
0 becomes <i>false</i> or <b>=E2=8A=A5</b>, and 1 becomes <i>true</i> or <b=
>=E2=8A=A4</b>. It is convenient when referring to generic propositions to =
use Greek letters =CE=A6, =CE=A8, ... as metavariables (variables outside t=
he language of propositional calculus, used when talking <i>about</i> propo=
sitional calculus) to denote propositions.
</p><p>The semantics of propositional logic rely on <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truth_assignment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Truth=
 assignment">truth assignments</a></i>. The essential idea of a truth assig=
nment is that the propositional variables are mapped to elements of a fixed=
 Boolean algebra, and then the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Truth_value" title=3D"Truth value">truth value</a></i> of a propositional f=
ormula using these letters is the element of the Boolean algebra that is ob=
tained by computing the value of the Boolean term corresponding to the form=
ula. In classical semantics, only the two-element Boolean algebra is used, =
while in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean-valued_semantics"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boolean-valued semantics">Boolean-valued se=
mantics</a> arbitrary Boolean algebras are considered. A <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tautology_(logic)" title=3D"Tautology (logic)">ta=
utology</a></i> is a propositional formula that is assigned truth value <i>=
1</i> by every truth assignment of its propositional variables to an arbitr=
ary Boolean algebra (or, equivalently, every truth assignment to the two el=
ement Boolean algebra).
</p><p>These semantics permit a translation between tautologies of proposit=
ional logic and equational theorems of Boolean algebra. Every tautology =CE=
=A6 of propositional logic can be expressed as the Boolean equation =CE=A6 =
=3D 1, which will be a theorem of Boolean algebra. Conversely, every theore=
m =CE=A6 =3D =CE=A8 of Boolean algebra corresponds to the tautologies (=CE=
=A6 =E2=88=A8 =C2=AC=CE=A8) =E2=88=A7 (=C2=AC=CE=A6 =E2=88=A8 =CE=A8) and (=
=CE=A6 =E2=88=A7 =CE=A8) =E2=88=A8 (=C2=AC=CE=A6 =E2=88=A7 =C2=AC=CE=A8). I=
f =E2=86=92 is in the language, these last tautologies can also be written =
as (=CE=A6 =E2=86=92 =CE=A8) =E2=88=A7 (=CE=A8 =E2=86=92 =CE=A6), or as two=
 separate theorems =CE=A6 =E2=86=92 =CE=A8 and =CE=A8 =E2=86=92 =CE=A6; if =
=E2=89=A1 is available, then the single tautology =CE=A6 =E2=89=A1 =CE=A8 c=
an be used.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_alge=
bra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Applications=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>One motivating application of propositional calculus is the analysis of =
propositions and deductive arguments in natural language.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Allwood_1977_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Allwood_1977-33"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Whereas the p=
roposition "if <i>x</i> =3D 3, then <i>x</i> + 1 =3D 4" depends on the mean=
ings of such symbols as + and 1, the proposition "if <i>x</i> =3D 3, then <=
i>x</i> =3D 3" does not; it is true merely by virtue of its structure, and =
remains true whether "<i>x</i> =3D 3" is replaced by "<i>x</i> =3D 4" or "t=
he moon is made of green cheese." The generic or abstract form of this taut=
ology is "if <i>P</i>, then <i>P</i>," or in the language of Boolean algebr=
a, <i>P</i> =E2=86=92 <i>P</i>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Templa=
te-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><sp=
an title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2020=
)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Replacing <i>P</i> by <i>x</i> =3D 3 or any other proposition is cal=
led <i>instantiation</i> of <i>P</i> by that proposition. The result of ins=
tantiating <i>P</i> in an abstract proposition is called an <i>instance</i>=
 of the proposition. Thus, <i>x</i> =3D 3 =E2=86=92 <i>x</i> =3D 3 is a tau=
tology by virtue of being an instance of the abstract tautology <i>P</i> =
=E2=86=92 <i>P</i>. All occurrences of the instantiated variable must be in=
stantiated with the same proposition, to avoid such nonsense as <i>P</i> =
=E2=86=92 <i>x</i> =3D 3 or <i>x</i> =3D 3 =E2=86=92 <i>x</i> =3D 4.
</p><p>Propositional calculus restricts attention to abstract propositions,=
 those built up from propositional variables using Boolean operations. Inst=
antiation is still possible within propositional calculus, but only by inst=
antiating propositional variables by abstract propositions, such as instant=
iating <i>Q</i> by <i>Q</i> =E2=86=92 <i>P</i> in <i>P</i> =E2=86=92 (<i>Q<=
/i> =E2=86=92 <i>P</i>) to yield the instance <i>P</i> =E2=86=92 ((<i>Q</i>=
 =E2=86=92 <i>P</i>) =E2=86=92 <i>P</i>).
</p><p>(The availability of instantiation as part of the machinery of propo=
sitional calculus avoids the need for metavariables within the language of =
propositional calculus, since ordinary propositional variables can be consi=
dered within the language to denote arbitrary propositions. The metavariabl=
es themselves are outside the reach of instantiation, not being part of the=
 language of propositional calculus but rather part of the same language fo=
r talking about it that this sentence is written in, where there is a need =
to be able to distinguish propositional variables and their instantiations =
as being distinct syntactic entities.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Deductive_systems_for_propo=
sitional_logic">Deductive systems for propositional logic</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Deductive systems for prop=
ositional logic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>An axiomatization of propositional calculus is a set of tautologies call=
ed <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axioms" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Axioms">axioms</a></i> and one or more inference rules for produ=
cing new tautologies from old. A <i>proof</i> in an axiom system <i>A</i> i=
s a finite nonempty sequence of propositions each of which is either an ins=
tance of an axiom of <i>A</i> or follows by some rule of <i>A</i> from prop=
ositions appearing earlier in the proof (thereby disallowing circular reaso=
ning). The last proposition is the <i>theorem</i> proved by the proof. Ever=
y nonempty initial segment of a proof is itself a proof, whence every propo=
sition in a proof is itself a theorem. An axiomatization is <i>sound</i> wh=
en every theorem is a tautology, and <i>complete</i> when every tautology i=
s a theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hausman-Tidman_2007_34-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Hausm=
an-Tidman_2007-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Sequent_calculus">Sequent c=
alculus</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Sequ=
ent calculus"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequent_calculus" ti=
tle=3D"Sequent calculus">Sequent calculus</a></div>
<p>Propositional calculus is commonly organized as a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_system" title=3D"Hilbert system">Hilbert system<=
/a>, whose operations are just those of Boolean algebra and whose theorems =
are Boolean tautologies, those Boolean terms equal to the Boolean constant =
1. Another form is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequent_calculu=
s" title=3D"Sequent calculus">sequent calculus</a>, which has two sorts, pr=
opositions as in ordinary propositional calculus, and pairs of lists of pro=
positions called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequent" title=
=3D"Sequent">sequents</a></i>, such as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i> =E2=
=88=A8 <i>B</i>, <i>A</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>C</i>, ... =E2=8A=A2 <i>A</i>, <i>B<=
/i> =E2=86=92 <i>C</i>, ....</span> The two halves of a sequent are called =
the antecedent and the succedent respectively. The customary metavariable d=
enoting an antecedent or part thereof is =CE=93, and for a succedent =CE=94=
; thus =CE=93, <i>A</i> =E2=8A=A2 =CE=94 would denote a sequent whose succe=
dent is a list =CE=94 and whose antecedent is a list =CE=93 with an additio=
nal proposition <i>A</i> appended after it. The antecedent is interpreted a=
s the conjunction of its propositions, the succedent as the disjunction of =
its propositions, and the sequent itself as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Entailment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Entailment">entail=
ment</a> of the succedent by the antecedent.
</p><p>Entailment differs from implication in that whereas the latter is a =
binary <i>operation</i> that returns a value in a Boolean algebra, the form=
er is a binary <i>relation</i> which either holds or does not hold. In this=
 sense, entailment is an <i>external</i> form of implication, meaning exter=
nal to the Boolean algebra, thinking of the reader of the sequent as also b=
eing external and interpreting and comparing antecedents and succedents in =
some Boolean algebra. The natural interpretation of =E2=8A=A2 is as =E2=89=
=A4 in the partial order of the Boolean algebra defined by <i>x</i> =E2=89=
=A4 <i>y</i> just when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A8 <i>y</i> =
=3D <i>y</i></span>. This ability to mix external implication =E2=8A=A2 and=
 internal implication =E2=86=92 in the one logic is among the essential dif=
ferences between sequent calculus and propositional calculus.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Girard-Tylor-Lafont_1989_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Girard-Tylor-Lafont_1989-3=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications_2">Application=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_al=
gebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Applicatio=
ns"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Boolean algebra as the calculus of two values is fundamental to computer=
 circuits, computer programming, and mathematical logic, and is also used i=
n other areas of mathematics such as set theory and statistics.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Givant-Halmos_2009_5-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-Givant-Halmos_2009-5"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computers">Computers</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebra&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Computers"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the early 20th century, several electrical engineers<sup class=3D"nop=
rint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_=
attributions" title=3D"Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span titl=
e=3D"The material near this tag possibly uses too-vague attribution or weas=
el words. (November 2022)">who?</span></a></i>]</sup> intuitively recognize=
d that Boolean algebra was analogous to the behavior of certain types of el=
ectrical circuits. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon"=
 title=3D"Claude Shannon">Claude Shannon</a> formally proved such behavior =
was logically equivalent to Boolean algebra in his 1937 master's thesis, <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Symbolic_Analysis_of_Relay_and_=
Switching_Circuits" title=3D"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Cir=
cuits">A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits</a></i>.
</p><p>Today, all modern general-purpose <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Computer">computers</a> perform their functions u=
sing two-value Boolean logic; that is, their electrical circuits are a phys=
ical manifestation of two-value Boolean logic. They achieve this in various=
 ways: as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_signal" title=3D=
"Digital signal">voltages on wires</a> in high-speed circuits and capacitiv=
e storage devices, as orientations of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Magnetic_storage" title=3D"Magnetic storage">magnetic domain</a> in f=
erromagnetic storage devices, as holes in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Punched_card" title=3D"Punched card">punched cards</a> or <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paper_tape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Paper tape">paper tape</a>, and so on. (Some early computers used decim=
al circuits or mechanisms instead of two-valued logic circuits.)
</p><p>Of course, it is possible to code more than two symbols in any given=
 medium. For example, one might use respectively 0, 1, 2, and 3 volts to co=
de a four-symbol alphabet on a wire, or holes of different sizes in a punch=
ed card. In practice, the tight constraints of high speed, small size, and =
low power combine to make noise a major factor. This makes it hard to disti=
nguish between symbols when there are several possible symbols that could o=
ccur at a single site. Rather than attempting to distinguish between four v=
oltages on one wire, digital designers have settled on two voltages per wir=
e, high and low.
</p><p>Computers use two-value Boolean circuits for the above reasons. The =
most common computer architectures use ordered sequences of Boolean values,=
 called bits, of 32 or 64 values, e.g. 01101000110101100101010101001011. Wh=
en programming in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_code" ti=
tle=3D"Machine code">machine code</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Assembly_language" title=3D"Assembly language">assembly language</a>, =
and certain other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_lang=
uages" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Programming languages">programming la=
nguages</a>, programmers work with the low-level digital structure of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_(data_type)" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Word (data type)">data registers</a>. These registers operate=
 on voltages, where zero volts represents Boolean 0, and a reference voltag=
e (often +5&nbsp;V, +3.3&nbsp;V, or +1.8&nbsp;V) represents Boolean 1. Such=
 languages support both numeric operations and logical operations. In this =
context, "numeric" means that the computer treats sequences of bits as <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary number"=
>binary numbers</a> (base two numbers) and executes arithmetic operations l=
ike add, subtract, multiply, or divide. "Logical" refers to the Boolean log=
ical operations of disjunction, conjunction, and negation between two seque=
nces of bits, in which each bit in one sequence is simply compared to its c=
ounterpart in the other sequence. Programmers therefore have the option of =
working in and applying the rules of either numeric algebra or Boolean alge=
bra as needed. A core differentiating feature between these families of ope=
rations is the existence of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
rry_(arithmetic)" title=3D"Carry (arithmetic)">carry</a> operation in the f=
irst but not the second.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Two-valued_logic">Two-value=
d logic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Two-=
valued logic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Other areas where two values is a good choice are the law and mathematic=
s. In everyday relaxed conversation, nuanced or complex answers such as "ma=
ybe" or "only on the weekend" are acceptable. In more focused situations su=
ch as a court of law or theorem-based mathematics, however, it is deemed ad=
vantageous to frame questions so as to admit a simple yes-or-no answer=E2=
=80=94is the defendant guilty or not guilty, is the proposition true or fal=
se=E2=80=94and to disallow any other answer. However, limiting this might p=
rove in practice for the respondent, the principle of the simple yes=E2=80=
=93no question has become a central feature of both judicial and mathematic=
al logic, making <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-valued_logic"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-valued logic">two-valued logic</a> dese=
rving of organization and study in its own right.
</p><p>A central concept of set theory is membership. An organization may p=
ermit multiple degrees of membership, such as novice, associate, and full. =
With sets, however, an element is either in or out. The candidates for memb=
ership in a set work just like the wires in a digital computer: each candid=
ate is either a member or a nonmember, just as each wire is either high or =
low.
</p><p>Algebra being a fundamental tool in any area amenable to mathematica=
l treatment, these considerations combine to make the algebra of two values=
 of fundamental importance to computer hardware, mathematical logic, and se=
t theory.
</p><p>Two-valued logic can be extended to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Multi-valued_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multi-valued lo=
gic">multi-valued logic</a>, notably by replacing the Boolean domain {0,&nb=
sp;1} with the unit interval [0,1], in which case rather than only taking v=
alues 0 or 1, any value between and including 0 and 1 can be assumed. Algeb=
raically, negation (NOT) is replaced with 1&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;<i>x</i>, c=
onjunction (AND) is replaced with multiplication (<i>xy</i>), and disjuncti=
on (OR) is defined via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Morgan%2=
7s_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"De Morgan's law">De Morgan's law</a>=
. Interpreting these values as logical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Truth_value" title=3D"Truth value">truth values</a> yields a multi-val=
ued logic, which forms the basis for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fuzzy_logic" title=3D"Fuzzy logic">fuzzy logic</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_logic" title=3D"Probabilistic logic">=
probabilistic logic</a>. In these interpretations, a value is interpreted a=
s the "degree" of truth =E2=80=93 to what extent a proposition is true, or =
the probability that the proposition is true.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Boolean_operations">Boolean=
 operations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Boolean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: =
Boolean operations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The original application for Boolean operations was <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">mathe=
matical logic</a>, where it combines the truth values, true or false, of in=
dividual formulas.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Natural_language">Natural l=
anguage</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Natu=
ral language"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Natural languages such as English have words for several Boolean operati=
ons, in particular conjunction (<i>and</i>), disjunction (<i>or</i>), negat=
ion (<i>not</i>), and implication (<i>implies</i>). <i>But not</i> is synon=
ymous with <i>and not</i>. When used to combine situational assertions such=
 as "the block is on the table" and "cats drink milk", which na=C3=AFvely a=
re either true or false, the meanings of these <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Logical_connective" title=3D"Logical connective">logical conne=
ctives</a> often have the meaning of their logical counterparts. However, w=
ith descriptions of behavior such as "Jim walked through the door", one sta=
rts to notice differences such as failure of commutativity, for example, th=
e conjunction of "Jim opened the door" with "Jim walked through the door" i=
n that order is not equivalent to their conjunction in the other order, sin=
ce <i>and</i> usually means <i>and then</i> in such cases. Questions can be=
 similar: the order "Is the sky blue, and why is the sky blue?" makes more =
sense than the reverse order. Conjunctive commands about behavior are like =
behavioral assertions, as in <i>get dressed and go to school</i>. Disjuncti=
ve commands such <i>love me or leave me</i> or <i>fish or cut bait</i> tend=
 to be asymmetric via the implication that one alternative is less preferab=
le. Conjoined nouns such as <i>tea and milk</i> generally describe aggregat=
ion as with set union while <i>tea or milk</i> is a choice. However, contex=
t can reverse these senses, as in <i>your choices are coffee and tea</i> wh=
ich usually means the same as <i>your choices are coffee or tea</i> (altern=
atives). Double negation, as in "I don't not like milk", rarely means liter=
ally "I do like milk" but rather conveys some sort of hedging, as though to=
 imply that there is a third possibility. "Not not P" can be loosely interp=
reted as "surely P", and although <i>P</i> necessarily implies "not not <i>=
P</i>," the converse is suspect in English, much as with <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intuitionistic_logic" title=3D"Intuitionistic logic"=
>intuitionistic logic</a>. In view of the highly idiosyncratic usage of con=
junctions in natural languages, Boolean algebra cannot be considered a reli=
able framework for interpreting them.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Digital_logic">Digital logi=
c</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_al=
gebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Digital lo=
gic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>Boolean operations are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Digital_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Digital logic">digital logic<=
/a> to combine the bits carried on individual wires, thereby interpreting t=
hem over {0,1}. When a vector of <i>n</i> identical binary gates are used t=
o combine two bit vectors each of <i>n</i> bits, the individual bit operati=
ons can be understood collectively as a single operation on values from a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(structure)" title=
=3D"Boolean algebra (structure)">Boolean algebra</a> with 2<sup><i>n</i></s=
up> elements.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Naive_set_theory">Naive set=
 theory</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Naiv=
e set theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory" title=3D"Naiv=
e set theory">Naive set theory</a> interprets Boolean operations as acting =
on subsets of a given set <i>X</i>. As we saw earlier this behavior exactly=
 parallels the coordinate-wise combinations of bit vectors, with the union =
of two sets corresponding to the disjunction of two bit vectors and so on.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Video_cards">Video cards</h=
4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBoolean_algebr=
a&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Video cards"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>The 256-element free Boolean algebra on three generators is deployed in =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_displays" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Computer displays">computer displays</a> based on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raster_graphics" title=3D"Raster graphics=
">raster graphics</a>, which use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
it_blit" title=3D"Bit blit">bit blit</a> to manipulate whole regions consis=
ting of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixels" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Pixels">pixels</a>, relying on Boolean operations to specify h=
ow the source region should be combined with the destination, typically wit=
h the help of a third region called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mask_(computing)" title=3D"Mask (computing)">mask</a>. Modern <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_cards" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Video cards">video cards</a> offer all <span class=3D"nowrap">2<sup>2<s=
pan><sup>3</sup></span></sup> =3D 256</span> ternary operations for this pu=
rpose, with the choice of operation being a one-byte (8-bit) parameter. The=
 constants <span class=3D"monospaced">SRC =3D 0xaa</span> or <link rel=3D"m=
w-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><sp=
an class=3D"monospaced">0b10101010</span>, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inl=
ine-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monosp=
aced">DST =3D 0xcc</span> or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hre=
f=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">0b110011=
00</span>, and <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:T=
emplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">MSK =3D 0xf0</span> or=
 <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:=
r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">0b11110000</span> allow Boolean oper=
ations such as <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-conten=
t-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">(SRC^DST)&amp;MSK</code> (meaning XOR the sou=
rce and destination and then AND the result with the mask) to be written di=
rectly as a constant denoting a byte calculated at compile time, <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734=
"><span class=3D"monospaced">0x80</span> in the <code class=3D"mw-highlight=
 mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">(SRC^DST)&am=
p;MSK</code> example, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw=
-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"><span class=3D"monospaced">0x88</span> if =
just <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" sty=
le=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">SRC^DST</code>, etc. At run time the video card interpr=
ets the byte as the raster operation indicated by the original expression i=
n a uniform way that requires remarkably little hardware and which takes ti=
me completely independent of the complexity of the expression.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Modeling_and_CAD">Modeling =
and CAD</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Mode=
ling and CAD"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_modeling" title=3D"Solid =
modeling">Solid modeling</a> systems for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Computer_aided_design" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computer aided=
 design">computer aided design</a> offer a variety of methods for building =
objects from other objects, combination by Boolean operations being one of =
them. In this method the space in which objects exist is understood as a se=
t <i>S</i> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voxel" title=3D"Voxe=
l">voxels</a> (the three-dimensional analogue of pixels in two-dimensional =
graphics) and shapes are defined as subsets of <i>S</i>, allowing objects t=
o be combined as sets via union, intersection, etc. One obvious use is in b=
uilding a complex shape from simple shapes simply as the union of the latte=
r. Another use is in sculpting understood as removal of material: any grind=
ing, milling, routing, or drilling operation that can be performed with phy=
sical machinery on physical materials can be simulated on the computer with=
 the Boolean operation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=A7 =C2=AC<i>=
y</i></span> or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=92 <i>y</i></span>,=
 which in set theory is set difference, remove the elements of <i>y</i> fro=
m those of <i>x</i>. Thus given two shapes one to be machined and the other=
 the material to be removed, the result of machining the former to remove t=
he latter is described simply as their set difference.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Boolean_searches">Boolean s=
earches</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBool=
ean_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Bool=
ean searches"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Search engine queries also employ Boolean logic. For this application, e=
ach web page on the Internet may be considered to be an "element" of a "set=
." The following examples use a syntax supported by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Google" title=3D"Google">Google</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-N=
B2_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boole=
an_algebra#cite_note-NB2-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>NB 1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Doublequotes are used to combine whitespace-separated words into a =
single search term.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NB3_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra#cite_note-NB3-37"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>NB 2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup></li>
<li>Whitespace is used to specify logical AND, as it is the default operato=
r for joining search terms:</li></ul>
<pre>"Search term 1" "Search term 2"
</pre>
<ul><li>The OR keyword is used for logical OR:</li></ul>
<pre>"Search term 1" OR "Search term 2"
</pre>
<ul><li>A prefixed minus sign is used for logical NOT:</li></ul>
<pre>"Search term 1" =E2=88=92"Search term 2"
</pre>
